TODO: remove deprecated item: regex rules

Since https://github.com/aureliojargas/txt2regex/pull/6, the regex
rules are based on the results of actually running the programs in a
Docker container, using a special script.

So now it's mandatory to first add the new program to that container
and properly test it. The process became even more complex as before,
but now it's reliable and tested.

commit.message:
Use quotes around $escape_metachar in escCharList

The expression uin="${uin/\\/$escape_metachar$escape_metachar}" has
different output on bash 5.2 then on earlier versions. Namely,
$escape_metachar is not treated as a string literal, so the escape
characters are applied which results in half as many escape chars in the
output:

  $ bash --version | head -1
  GNU bash, version 5.2.0(1)-rc2 (x86_64-pc-linux-gnu)
  $ uin='[\]'; escape_metachar='\\'; echo ${uin/\\/$escape_metachar$escape_metachar}
  [\\]

  vs.

  $ bash --version | head -1
  GNU bash, version 5.1.16(1)-release (x86_64-pc-linux-gnu)
  $ uin='[\]'; escape_metachar='\\'; echo ${uin/\\/$escape_metachar$escape_metachar}
  [\\\\]

To fix this, add quotes around $escape_metachar in this substitution:

  $ bash --version | head -1
  GNU bash, version 5.2.0(1)-rc2 (x86_64-pc-linux-gnu)
  $ uin='[\]'; escape_metachar='\\'; echo ${uin/\\/"$escape_metachar$escape_metachar"}
  [\\\\]

On bash versions 4.2 and earlier, the extra quotes will show up in the
output, so make the use of quotes conditional on the bash major version
number being 5 or higher.

Makefile: test-bash: Early exit in the first error

Errors in the previous bash versions were undetected, because this
target would exit as successful when the last tested bash version
was successful.

Now with the early exit, we make sure this target is aborted and
exit with error when the first tested bash version fails.

The downside is that we don't get all the fails in a single run, in
case more than one bash version fails. Well, we can't have
everything.

Makefile: Avoid unsupported path globs: {foo,bar}

By default, the make command execute the shell commands using `sh`, not
`bash`. So more advanced glob patterns such as `{foo,bar}` are not
supported.

Those patterns were expanded to multiple paths, instead of telling
make to use bash instead (unnecessary dependency and maybe would
bring unexpected problems).

lint: Quote array expansion (SC2048)

SC2048 (warning): Use "${array[@]}" (with quotes) to prevent
whitespace problems.

lint: Add missing double quotes (SC2086)

SC2086 (info): Double quote to prevent globbing and word splitting.

lint: Ignore SC2256, not relevant

    SC2256: This translated string is the name of a variable.
    Flip leading $ and " if this should be a quoted substitution.

In our case, this is really a translated string, not a quoted
substitution.

tests: Fix weird clitest + head + GitHub Actions bug

The previous code fails when running in GitHub Actions:

    [FAILED #39, line 384] txt2regex --foo | head -n 3 | sed '3 s/:.*//'
    @@ -1,3 +1,21 @@
    +./txt2regex.sh: line 115: printf: write error: Broken pipe
    +./txt2regex.sh: line 117: printf: write error: Broken pipe
    +./txt2regex.sh: line 119: printf: write error: Broken pipe
    +./txt2regex.sh: line 121: printf: write error: Broken pipe
    +./txt2regex.sh: line 122: printf: write error: Broken pipe
    +./txt2regex.sh: line 123: printf: write error: Broken pipe
     --foo: invalid option

     usage

Even when changing `head -n 3` to `sed 3q` it failed with the same
error.

When doing a single sed after the first pipe it worked fine *once*.
In the next run it failed again, with the same error.
I don't know what's happening, to be honest.

Trying with a temporary file, to avoid piping the first command.
